deck_excerpt: I- I made ninjas kinda playable. . .
deck_description: So basically you are making Goliath with super transformation. In the side deck, there is a way to get into Dark Simorgh against back row decks. You can put ani-spell to synergize with the Dark Simorgh if you would like, but I found it not necessary. The overall goal is to get to Goliath or Sloth. Pros: The deck actually has a surprisingly good win rate! The field spell can allow for your Saizo to become similar to a towers as long as you have a monster onboard and a ninja in the grave witch can be very useful. I've won games because my opponent cannot out Saizo and then I just drop a Goliath and win. This deck is NOT an aggressive deck and you win by staying up in resources. I find the deck very fun, and it does amazing in the grind game. Cons: It is very meta-dependent. It is good against certain decks in our format, but that changes depending on the match-up. It does not have a great match-up against drytron and against flundereeze, the idea is to stop extra deck decks from going into the extra deck, but any level one decks also are not great because you have to improvise to get into Goliath/Sloth (I once pen summoned tribute fodder for my sloth using two monsters in my deck that just happened to be scales). Lastly, it struggles with monster removal. Conclusion: The deck actually puts up a decent fight against most decks but is very meta-dependent. I hope you have fun with the deck! Feedback is greatly appreciated!

deck_excerpt: The deck plays the standard original playstyle of Witchcrafters, removing the janky spell chronicle portion and playing a slower control/board-breakin
deck_description:
The deck plays the standard original playstyle of Witchcrafters, removing the janky spell chronicle portion and playing a slower control/board-breaking build that plays well both going first and second. For those who don't know, the deck consists of spellcasters of various levels and attributes that activate their effects by discarding spell cards from your hand, this makes them seem resource intensive but all the archetype spells can add themselves back to the hand during your end phase. With the inclusion of the new fusion, the deck became much stronger even though the fusion spell is sort of mediocre. I found the deck suitable as a control deck that uses the extra deck as a toolbox, hence I chose not to run neither extravagance nor prosperity in the main deck as of the current moment.    Deck starters going first: Witchcrafters (level4 & under): they tribute themselves and discard any spell to special summon another Witchcrafter of any level from deck; due to this they are very fragile to handtraps and negation, hence playing gamma and driver is necessary in this deck, and going into Chaos ruler can help fill your GY with cards. - Witchcrafter Unveiling : Special summon any Witchcrafter monster in hand and can give your monsters immunity when activating their effects, the Witchcraft monsters already dodge Infinite Impermanence and Skill drain well, they have a problem with handtraps, this can help play around them.  -Reasoning: Automatic inclusion in the deck as they are diverse in levels and the smaller Witchcrafters have effects in the GY, you also don't mind having the in-theme spells and monsters in GY, as you can banish a spell along with Witchcrafter Genni to extend play; recovery of card with Witchcrafter Potterie with an empty hand; Magician's Restage can activate adding the floodgate hands; worst case scenario the spells add themselves to hand at the End-phase when you at least placed a boss card on the field. -Gamma and Driver : mentioned a couple of times already, together they can help you go into chaos ruler and fill your GY, and they can also go into a link 2 like Lyna the light charmer or lambda and build up into a Selene, Queen of the master magicians for an OTK. -Magicians' Soul : Sends Witchcrafter Hanie or Madame Verre from deck to GY as cost, but also a free special summon with Anima and Linkuriboh as a tech option, being a (Dark) [Spellcaster] makes it a wonderful inclusion in the deck with the Witchcrafter Confusion spell and a Super polymerization target. It can also be re-summoned by restage, and last but not least it helps you draw cards by discarding and/or sending spells from field or hands. All around good card that could be a staple in the main deck. Deck starters going Second: -Super Polymerization: it is an absolute beast of a card this meta, with a diverse set of targets that can hit most of the meta decks, best thing is there is little your opponent can do against you, they can't even play secret village of spellcasters against you, this is especially useful because people are not ending on large boards with many negates this format, so super poly can hit invoked-Dogmatika(Shaddoll Winda - Mudragon - Witchcrafter vice-master) Eldlich(the mad golden lord) Prank-kids (Rocket ride) Tribrigade/birds(Guardragon Almarduk) Common Dark types can be beat with starving venom/Predaplant Triphyoveretum/Predaplant Dracostapelia(live-twins,DPE, etc........ Swordsoul is probably the most difficult deck to out. -Instant Fusion: Thousand-eyes/Millennium-eyes into Restrict Anima, but that is probably a long stretch, both targets can be summoned w/ Magician's Restage
Extra-deck explained: [5-6]cards of the deck is a fusion toolbox consisting of 2 Witchcrafter Vice-master, Super-poly targets and/or instant fusion targets. Since the inclusion of the a Witchcrafter fusion monster, I've found success and synergy in using instant fusion, super polymerization. This can be reduced to 3 slots if you side/remove super-poly  [1 slot for a level 8 synchro], I've found most success with Chaos ruler since it can set up the graveyard for you and it can revive itself once very easily to go into access-code talker finisher, but the options are limitless depending on what you feel you need for the deck [1 slot for a Rank8] Witchcrafter Aruru, Madame Verre, and Vice-master are all level 8: some viable options can include Dingirsu/Sanaphond the Skyprison/Number 38: Hope Harbinger/ Lancelot, the option to run a Rank8 is optional and running more than 1 is unnecessary since it rarely comes up [Rest of the ExtraDeck is Links] Charmers compliment the deck very well, not only because they are cute girls as well, but because you run a diverse attribute of spellcasters. The most viable ones are probably Hiita, Aussa, and Lyna: most because they can summon handtraps from your opponents deck Ash Blossom/Ghost belle/Effect Veiler respectively, this sets up a guaranteed Link 3 into Selene. Selene + AccessCode Talker are an expensive duo to run, but it is a game closer, Access code's 5300 atk + Vice-master's 2700 atk = a clean 8000 damage, together you are guaranteed  from minimum 3 to 4 pops on the field at least, this will win you games on its own not much to say Artemis/Anima/Linkuriboh can place your Witchcrafters in deck, all 3 are good in certain situations but above all Artemis has the most versatility since it can be made by any of the small Witchcrafters and is a spellcaster, anima is also a spellcaster and it can catch your opponent offguard, but is a side option since they are less likely to fall for the same trick twice. Linkuriboh can be useful to blink Genni, souls and the restricts but sadly it isn't a spellcaster, so I don't blame you if you don't run it, but on field it can save you from an attack. Verte Anaconda/Psyframelord Lambda verte has 3 targets in deck superpoly/instant fusion/Witchcrafter confusion and if you are really bold magicalized fusion is a tech option, but try to banish souls/restrict/anima/any charmer instead of 2 Witchcrafters, since you can make use of the Witchcrafters effect or revive them with holiday. Psyframelord is a generic Link-2 that is light that can turn a dead gamma in your hand live in worst case scenario.  The healthy amount of Dark and light in the extradeck makes reborning Chaos Lord very easy, but it is banished when it leaves the field...unless you make a rank 8 and  detach it then you can do it again.

deck_excerpt: Gagaga deck, onomatopaira, onomatopickup, Invoked, Dogmatika, Beatrice, Lady of the eternal , Traptrix rafflesia
deck_description: 1 card combo:  Onomatopaira (onomatopickup is counted as onomatopaira also):  How to make a board to get rid of 3 opponent monsters:  1- Activate it, discard 1 card  2- take zubaba bancho + gagaga sister  3- normal sumon gagaga sister, use eff and take gagagarevenge  4- special summon zubaba bancho from your hand  5- use eff of gagaga sister and make both level 6  6- summon Beatrice from extra deck and use eff  by detaching zubaba bancho and send Utopic Onomatopoeia in grave  7- activate gagagarevenge and special summon zubaba bancho  8- activata eff of zubaba bancho and special summon utopic onomatopeia from the grave  9- summon traptrix rafflesia  TIP: In your opponent turn, you can use eff of traptrix rafflesia to send in grave Treacherous Hole to destroy 2 monster and you can use the eff of Beatrice to send in the grave Tackle Crusader and use his eff to change 1 face up monster in face down defense position .     Next combo with Onomatopaira (onomatopickup) to summon Dark Dragoon:  1-activate and discard 1 card  2- take Utopic Onomato. and zubaba bancho  3 - summon utopic onomat. but don't use his eff, after that special summon from your hand zubaba bancho by using the own eff of zubaba bancho  4- summon predaplant verte and use his eff and vualla you have the Dark Dragoon     TIP: There is important cards in this deck because of the hand traps  If you have in your hand LinkSlayer or Parallel exceed , be sure that you can survive if your opponent use hand trap (ash, veiller, impermanence etc).  Special summon LinkSlayer and normal summon Alisteir the invoker (search him with meltdown) and summon salamangreat almiraj, after summon Predaplant verte and use eff to summon dark dragoon. If you have Parallel exceed you can do the same thing but you can special summon it from hand when u summon Almiraj.  If you special summon LinkSlayer but u use Onomatopaira combo and  the opponent use veiller or impremanence etc.. on gagaga sister , then u can special summon zubaba bancho from hand and summon predaplant verte and use his eff to summon Dark dragoon.  If you have Parallel exceed in hand , you can summon salamangreat almiraj using Gagaga sister and then special summon parallel exceed and then summon predaplant verte, use eff and summon dark dragoon.  TIP (only for onomatopaira combo): you have 2 predaplant verte in case the opponent use negate on the first one, so if you use onomatopaira combo and u summon the first predaplant verte ,make sure you use the first eff to make a monster dark antribute ,in this way u will provoke the opponent to use negate, and then summon the second predaplant verte and use his eff to summon dark dragoon.  Dogmatika combo and Invoker combo is same, i am lazy to write them, i will just mention this deck is not using Punishment in the dogmatika engine because here is 11 perfect starter cards (meltdown, alisteir, onomatopickup and onomatopaira) so believe me that u don't want to lock your extra deck!  In this deck is not terraforming and not 3 copies of alisteir and not 2 copies of invocation  because u already have 11 perfect starter cards in total...  The 2 Kaiju in the deck is usually to get rid of boss monster and is very helpful ,2 droplet is perfectly fine (u don't want more, sometimes u cant afford the cost)  Some TIPS:  if u are going first, Zeus in the extra deck is usually summoned using Traptrix rafflesia  If u want to use Zeus when u are going second , onomatopaira combo: when u summon beatrice and use the eff to send in gy utopic onomat. attack 1 monster and then summon zeus, use eff of zeus and the field is clear:D , after that use gagagarevenge to special summon bancho and summon predaplant verte and use eff to summon dark dragoon , or if u want to keep zeus on the field , use eff of bancho to sp. summon utopic onomat. from gy and summon traptrix rafflesia .  so is your choice if u want only dragoon or zeus(no materials) + traptrix rafflesia.     In the side deck is sacred tree beast, u can summon it by gagaga magician and gagagawind. how:  onomatopaira combo: take gagaga sister + gagaga magician, summon gagaga sister and use eff to take gagagawind. use gagagwind and summon gagaga magician, use eff to make him level 7, use eff of sister to make them level 9 and summon sacred tree beast.  i am lazy to write more combos, the deck is good. enjoy     CREATED SPECIALLY BY ME: DENIS.

deck_name: Albaz Despia (Post Albaz Strike Structure Deck)
deck_excerpt: New Albaz support is here! Spam Fusion summons with the new Branded Spells and win with powerful Dragons!
deck_description: The Despia strategy is heavily focused on searching the "Branded" Spell and Traps cards and to Fusion summon, something that the Fallen of Albaz needs to be playable, and with the new support coming for the Branded cards and Albaz in the next Structure Deck, it's sure to be one of the new best decks of the format. Cards like Branded Fusion and Paradise Branded allows you to use Monsters from your Deck as fusion material and gets you a search when fusion summoning. Aluber the Jester of Despia can search any Branded Spell or Trap on it's summon and can also be played during the opponent's turn with Branded Opening, making it a great searcher for the deck, but so does Springans Kitt because if you control a Fusion Monster that lists Fallen of Albaz such as Albion the Branded Dragon as one of it's materials, you can special summon it from your hand and either search a Braned Spell/Trap from your Deck or add one back from your Graveyard or even banished. Overall, the Branded engine is one of if not the strongest fusion engine at the momment, usually ending on multiple Fusion Monsters like one or two Masquerade the Blazing Dragon and a Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon.

deck_excerpt: Dragon Link Deck Profile With Combo Tutorial
deck_description: The Yu-Gi-Oh! Trading Card Game Known as the Yu-Gi-Oh! Official Card Game (遊☆戯☆王オフィシャルカードゲーム, Yū-Gi-Ō Ofisharu Kādo Gēmu) in Asia, is a Japanese collectible card game developed and published by Konami. It is based on the fictional game of Duel Monsters created by manga artist Kazuki Takahashi, which is the main plot device during the majority of the manga franchise, Yu-Gi-Oh, and its various anime adaptations and spinoff series.  "Rocket", known in the OCG as either "Vullet" or "Varrett"[1] (ヴァレット Varetto), is an archetype of DARK Dragon monsters used by Roken Kogami/Varis in the Yu-Gi-Oh! VRAINS anime. All "Rokket" monsters are legless, mechanical Dragons, with heads shaped like various types of ammunition, and green hard-light wings (except "Silverrokket Dragon" and "Rokket Caliber", whose wings are magenta). Strategy for this deck : 1. Make sure when you use the "Dragunity Remus" Special Summon effect from the graveyard you already summoned "Crystron Halqifibrax" first.  2. deck_excerpt: A casual and fun Galaxy/Photon Dragon deck.
deck_description:
Este deck de dragão de fótons tem um poder ofensivo muito alto, seja usando o efeito Galaxy-Eyes Full Armor Photon Dragon para desassociar o Afterglow e destruir uma carta virada para cima no campo e convocar um dragão de fótons como um bônus e causar cerca de 7000 de dano, ou de forma mais sólida, use o Número 62 e desassocie Pós-luminescência para aumentar durante a etapa de dano para causar dano maior que 10000.

Number 62 is the most powerful card on the deck in terms of attack thanks to its effect along with Afterglow, you would normally destroy any monster with this monstrous attack, but Full Armor with its effect can destroy a card on the field, which can be quite useful , by disassociating Afterglow, you can choose between associating a Photon Dragon to it directly from the deck and summoning Cipher Blade from Full Armor and having either a destruction effect and a float effect that I didn't particularly use or summoning it and having two monsters with 4000 and 3000 attack.

Number 90 and Neo Galaxy-Eyes are pretty consistent control options, with Number 90 being great for the 1st turn and Neo Galaxy-Eyes being a great option to negate the effects of everyone except himself on the field, in addition to having a gain effect of not-so-disposable attack.  Starliege and Galaxion are options to summon a Photon Dragon from your hand or deck, Solflare is a card I found pretty expendable to be honest I'm not a great player so maybe I haven't found a good use for this link anyway way it's good to have a copy of it, luckily these 3 monsters can be summoned from Photon Sanctuary tokens as far as I know.

Foolish Burial and Trade-in are cards you'll see so often, but they have their niches and can send a Photon Dragon to the Graveyard from the Deck or Hand respectively, either to Summon it from the Graveyard using Return of Dragon Lords, Monster Reborn or Galaxy Trance, or draw 2 cards for the Trade-In effect.  There are many ways to summon Photon Dragon from the hand, deck or graveyard, Galaxy Expedition is another great way to summon monsters and even the Photon itself from the deck, but Cloudragon definitely stands out when it comes to summoning Photon Dragon, even if not summoning directly from the deck , Summoning from the hand and Graveyard makes it a good option, in addition to its effect of associating with a Xyz monster, one of its qualities is that it can be summoned directly from the deck by the good Accellight effect that allows you to summon a monster level 4 or lower directly from your deck if you don't control a monster, its cost can make you think twice when using it, but it's not something that alarming, 2 copies seem to be a good choice, I confess that this card would be much better if you could summon others Photon monsters from the deck, but I don't know if she's capable of that or not.

In the extra deck I put some support cards and other possible Xyz options for the deck, I confess I haven't tested them, I apologize for that, in addition to the basic strategies there are also moves involving Galaxy Soldier discard a monster to summon and add Galaxy monster from the deck, and Galaxy Brave which honestly, together with Galaxy Knight (which I didn't even put on the deck) I thought it was quite unnecessary, even with a copy of it, some other support would probably suit this deck well, something to make it more consistent is always welcome, as a whole I think this is a good deck, but probably not enough to face stronger decks, I suppose the deck lacks consistency. Any feedback I would be immensely grateful, I didn't watch Zexal's anime, but I fell in love with this archetype.

Atualization 1

portanto, deve ser ignorado quando pelo Galaxy Expedition e Galaxy Trance, a melhor combinação com ele, até onde testei, é usar o efeito Galaxy Soldier, descartando um Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon adicionado ao Galaxy Knight do deck, convoque-o para seu efeito e convoque o "Dragão de Fótons de Olhos de Galáxia" do cemitério. Tirando essa carta, não há muito mais a acrescentar, Accellight ainda é uma boa carta, mas com uma limitação um tanto chata, lembro-me de uma ou duas vezes que tive Galaxy Knight em minha mão pronto para puxar um Photon Dragon do cemitério. , mas eu não pude por causa do efeito Accellight, Return Of Dragon Lords provou ser uma ótima carta, pois além de convocar os dois dragões do deck principal (Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon e Galaxy-Eyes Afterglow Dragon) do cemitério,

deck_excerpt: A deck using the Ancient Gear archetype
deck_description: INTRODUCTION This is another one of my personal favorite decks, and I honestly have no idea why. It's the only archetype from GX that I remotely enjoy, and honestly, that may be because it only uses fusions lol. Anyway, this deck should be good for use, however, the only thing I see bad with it is bricking with all spells/traps. But let's focus on the strat. DECK STRATEGY The first thing you want to look for is your deck to hand cards, like Ancient Gear Frame, and Ancient Gear Wyvern. Then, no matter first thing you get is Ancient Gear Fusion to get out one of ya boys from the extra deck. I would personally get out Chaos Ancient Gear Giant since it's the only one with 3 copies in the extra deck, and it's the deck master. The next thing you have to do is hold out for more fusions cards, whether you add them to your hand or draw them. GET OUT ANCIENT GEAR MEGATRON GOLEM, NO QUESTIONS ASKED. It allows you to get out Ultimate Ancient Gear Golem without using a fusion card like Ancient Gear Fusion or Ancient Gear Hunting Hound. Finally, just absolutely f**kin beat down your opponent. Try your best to get out Ancient Gear Golem - Ultimate Pound, since it can help OTK. You don't have to, but it'll help secure the win. OTHER STRATEGIES Reactor Dragon Assembly Summon/Reactor Dragon Backrow Protection To do this, the thing you want to do is keep searching the Ancient Gear cards that have destruction effects. For example, Geartown lets you special summon 1 Ancient Gear monster from your hand, deck, or graveyard when destroyed. Look for cards like that, and get them on the field. And then, you NEED to get out Ancient Gear Reactor Dragon, so you can destroy those cards to get more summons in during the battle phase. USE ANCIENT GEAR GADGET FOR ITS SUMMON!!! This allows it to attack twice, so you need it to maximize spell destruction and then summons.

deck_excerpt: AKA Zombie World: The New Generation
deck_description: Last but not least, we have the Triple Structure Deck Challenge for the Zombie Horde Structure Deck to finalize this definitely not delayed by 2 months Halloween special. In the Zombie Madness decklist I left the 2 new rules that will be used from now on in the series, but to summarize: - The Deck's plyastyle must play around thier boss monster, and said boss monster must be featured at 3 at all times. However, this is one of the Structure Decks where a special case happens that more than 1 monster is featured in its cover. In that case, there has to be a combination of 3 cards along said monsters. - The Extra Deck must be built depending on the time the Structure Deck was printed and if it has any Extra Deck monsters or has access to them. ANALYSIS One thing some people don't know is that this Deck forms part of an new OCG series of prebuilt decks known there as the R Series (which I'm gonna assume stands for Revisited given the nature this Decks tend to have). This series focuses on one thing: take an old Structure Deck, retrain their main Boss Monster with a better array of effects, add a few new playmakers that fill the theme of both the Deck and the current meta and it's ready to go. In this case, alongside creating a new version of Zombie World's boss monster, they also added another one and splashed some new cards that not only interact with Zombie monsters but also when Zombie World is live. On a kind of rare situation, this Deck features 2 boss monsters. First we have Red-Eyes Zombie Necro Dragon, which is a retrain version of Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon. Is a Level 7 DARK Zombie Synchro monster and requires a Tuner and 1 or more non-Tuners. It gains 100 ATK/DEF for each Zombie monster on the field and both GYs. Also, when another Zombie monster is destroyed by battle, it can Special Summon one Zombie monster from any GY to your field. Even if Zombie World is on the field or not, Necro Dragon can turn into a good beater that its revival effect acts more like recovery for your destroyed monsters. But if Zombie World is on, its stats can go way higher, can steal some good playmakers from the opponent's GY and can use them for any Extra Deck play needed. The other Boss Monster is Doomking Balerdroch, a Level 8 DARK Zombie with 2800 ATK/2000 DEF. During the Standby Phase, if this card is on the GY while a Field Spell is on the field face-up: you can Special Summon it on face-up Defense Position. Also, once per Chain you can activate 1 of these effects on response to the effect activation of a Zombie monster: -Negate that effect. -Banish 1 monster on the field or either GY. All of this effects are hard OPT, but their usefulness more than compensates for it. It returns every turn, making it a reliable material for Xyz and Link plays as well as being hard to get rid off, and his effects can be triggered by your own monsters or the opponents', so you can apply the banish effect each turn and apply the negates against your opponent. Since the new rule says that a combination of 3 cards must be used among these cards, I went with 2 Doomkings and 1 Necro Dragon, giving that this deck can have a quite generous Extra Deck toolbox. As for their playstyle, they take the focus on GY and monster stealing that Zombie World started and reinforced it, as well as giving them new tools to access their higher Level monsters and Extra Deck faster. BREAKDOWN *Eldlich the Golden Lord: Easy to summon body with high stats and good effects, even if this Deck runs more monsters than backrow. *Hela, Generaider Boss of Doom: Another easy to summon monster than can tribute 1 Zombie monster to revive another one with a different name. **Doomking Balerdroch: One of the two Boss Monster of the Deck, granting disruption and being hard to get rid off. *Jack-o-Bolan: Easy summoning condition. Can revive a Zombie monster from any GY at the cost of banishing himself for the rest of the turn. ***Necroworld Banshee: Main searcher and protector of Zombie World. ***Gozuki: Zombie miller. It can Special Summon a Zombie from the hand if he is sent to the GY. ***Mezuki: Can banish itself from the GY to revive a Zombie monster. Very useful for play extension. ***Shiranui Solitaire: Can tribute any Zombie monster to Special Summon a Zombie from the Deck with 0 DEF. Gives access to 2 of your main Tuners. ***Uni-Zombie: One of your main Tuners. Can dump a Zombie from the hand or Deck to change the Level of a monster. Accesible by Solitaire's effect. ***Glow-Up Bloom: Your other main Tuner, but you will mostly use it for its GY effect. Can cheat out or search high Level Zombie monsters from the Deck, depending if Zombie World is on the field. **Book of Life: Good revival card for Zombie decks, but requires setup. *Harpie's Feather Duster: Backrow removal. ***Monster Gate: Really useful if paired with Bloom, Mezuki or Gozuki. *Upstart Goblin: Giving that there are more non-DARK monsters on the Main Deck, using Allure of Darkness can be risky. *Card Destruction: Hand refresher. *Foolish Burial: Simple mill effect, giving that any monster can benefit from it. *Monster Reborn: Simple revival effect. ***Zombie World: Your Homeland. Lets most of your bigger monsters to interact with your opponent's field and GY. *Metaverse: Can search or activate Zombie World directly from the Deck. ***Rivalry of the Warlords: If paired with Zombie World, it can heavily slow your opponents plays. Prone to removal though. Extra Deck: *Chaos Ruler, the Chaotic Magical Dragon: Generic Level 8 Synchro that can potentially add 1 LIGHT or DARK monster from your Deck to the hand while also milling 4 cards. Even if you fail the search, whatever monsters you mill are still useful. *Borreload Savage Dragon: Generic Level 8 Synchro with negation. *Draco Berserker of the Tenyi: Generic Level 8 Synchro for monster hate. *Psy-Framelord Omega: Generic Level 8 Synchro for hand ripping and for recycling banished monsters. *Red-Eyes Zombie Necro Dragon: Generic Level 7 Synchro and second Boss Monster of the Deck. Can reach high stats and can revive any Zombie when another one is destroyed by battle. *The Undead Vampire: Generic Rank 8 Xyz Monster that can also use 2 monsters that were originally from your opponent for its summon. Can mill 4 cards from each Deck and revive one monster milled by its effect. *Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy: Generic Rank 8 Xyz monster with Spell negation and can redirect attacks. *Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star: Generic Level 8 Xyz monster with non targeting removal and mass destruction protection. *Yuki-Onna, the Absolute Zero Mayakashi: Link 4 for Zombies that can negate the effects of face-up monsters and reduce their ATK to 0 in response to a revival, twice per turn. *Accesscode Talker: Link 4 monster and potential game ender. Can reach high attack values and has Spell Speed 4 removal. *Vampire Fascinator: Link 3 for Zombie monsters. Steals a monster from the opponents' GY on Link Summon and can tribute a "Vampire" monster, including herself, to steal a monster your opponent controls. Gives easy access to Absolute Zero and The Undead Vampire. *Yuki-Onna, the Icicle Mayakashi: Link 3 for Zombie monsters. Negates the effects of a monster on Special Summon and can banish itself from the GY to Special Summon 1 Zombie Synchro Monster from the GY or that is banished. *Shiranui Skillsaga Supremacy: Link 3 for Zombie monsters. Cannot be destroyed by battle and prevents Synchro monsters from being destroyed by card effects. Can bring a banished Zombie Synchro monster to a zone it points to. *Vampire Sucker: Link 2 for Zombie monsters. Lets you Tribute Summon Zombie monsters using your opponent's Zombie monsters. Can revive a monster from the opponent's GY to their field and draws 1 if a Zombie monster is Special Summoned from the GY. Very useful with Doomking. *Avendread Savior: Link 2 for Zombie monsters. During damage calculation, it can mill 1 Zombie monster to reduce the ATK of the monster is battling with. Very useful to get the higher Level Zombies, like Doomking, on the GY. And this should be it for this very delayed Halloween special. I already programmed my next upload for mid to late January, in which will be looking to 3 Dragon-themed Structure Decks: Rise of the Dragon Lords, Rise of the True Dragons and the newly and fully revealed Albaz Strike Structure Decks. Until then, take care.

deck_excerpt: Featuring the Red-Eyes monster that never was because a lack of potential.
deck_description: Following the Zombie Madness list, now is turn for the Triple Structure Deck Challenge for the Zombie World Structure Deck. If haven't read the new rules for this challenge, I'll summarize: - The built decks now must focus on the main boss monster's playstyle and must be featured at 3 at all times. - The Extra Deck must be built around if the Deck even has Extra Deck monsters or had access to depending the era it was printed. ANALYSIS Being printed during the 5D's era, Zombie World bring a whole new wave of support to the Zombie playstyle, mostly the GY manipulation part, and decides to add new cards that interact with Zombie monsters from your opponent's GY. How? Because of the namesake of this Deck is printed, Zombie World. It also decides to add a new playstyle to the Zombie mechanics, that being changing the types of all monsters to Zombies and stealing monsters from the opponent's GY. Their featured Boss Monster is Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon. Is a Level 7 DARK Zombie with 2400 ATK/2000 DEF that can be Tribute Summoned in Attack Position using only 1 Zombie monster as Tribute. When it destroys a Zombie monster by battle and sends it to the GY: You can Special Summon it to your field. Like a repeating case with the last decklist, this deck offers another ways to Summon him quicker, although its summoning condition is not that restrictive either. If you're crazy enough, I guess you can mix Red-Eyes support to this build to search him faster or reviving him, but I'll leave that to your preference. Giving that this deck was printed during the 5D's era, it will feature some Synchros and Fusion monsters, but I enssured no way-too-recent monsters were on it. BREAKDOWN Main Deck: ***Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon: Main Boss Monster. It steals any Zombie monster it destroys by battle and is fairy easy to summon. ***Paladin of the Cursed Dragon: Solid Level 4 beater. Can revive any Level 4 or lower Zombie monster from your opponent's GY that was destroyed by battle. ***Necroworld Banshee(Outside Support): Can both protect Zombie World as well as activating more copies from the hand or Deck. ***Zombie Master: By discarding a monster it can revive a Level 4 or lower Zombie monster from any GY. ***Mezuki(Outside Support): Can mill a Zombie OPT and it can Special Summon a Zombie monster from the hand if it is sent to the GY. ***Pyramid Turtle: Really good floater. Can float even into REZD. *Spirit Reaper: Emergency battle staller. **Plaguespreader Zombie: Main Tuner of the Deck, can revive itself by returing a card to the top of the Deck. **Book of Life: Revival card for Zombie monsters but requires setup. *Pot of Avarice: Recycling and draw power. **Dragon's Mirror(Outside Support): Used to summon Nethersoul. *Card Destruction(Outside Support): Hand refresher, giving that some monsters can work well on the GY and can let you use Book of Life turn 1. *Terraforming(Outside Support): Searchs Zombie World. ***Call of the Mummy: Zombie-themed Valhalla. ***Zombie World: Turns all monsters on the field and GYs to Zombies and neither player can Tribute Summon except Zombie monsters. Main enabler for most of your playmakers. ***Waboku: Battle protection. ***Bottomless Trap Hole: Disruption for your opponents' summons. Extra Deck: **Dragonecro Nethersoul Dragon: Cannot destroy monsters by battle but it reduces its ATK to 0 and spawns a Token with ATK and Level equal to that monster's. Accesible with Dragon's Mirror due to being and original Dragon-type. *Leo, the Keeper of the Sacred Tree: Generic Level 10 Synchro with targeting protection. *Giganticastle: Generic Level 9 Synchro that can be a large beater. *Trishula, Dragon of the Ice Barrier: Enough explaining why, is just Trish. *Iron Chain Dragon: Generic Level 6 Synchro. Good beater with milling effect. *Red Wyvern: Generic Level 6 Synchro with potential Quick monster removal. *HTS Psyhemuth: Generic Level 6 Synchro that can banish any monster it battles alongside himself. **Doomkaiser Dragon: Steals any Zombie monster from your opponent's GY when Special Summoned by any means. More specific to summon. *Celestial Wolf Lord, Blue Sirius: Generic Level 6 Synchro and debuffer. *Coral Dragon: Generic Level 6 Synchro Tuner with targeted destruction and draw power. *Brionac, Dragon of the Ice Barrier: Generic Level 6 Synchro with good bouncing effect. *Armades, Keeper of Boundaries: Generic Level 5 Synchro and solid beater. *Ally of Justice Catastor: Generic Level 5 Synchro that can destroy any non-DARK monster.

deck_excerpt: Remember that one time Vampires were not an Archetype yet?
deck_description: Remember that time I promised I would bring 3 Zombie Structure Decks for the challenge all the way back on Halloween? Well, after finally entering the last weeks of school I finally have some time to bring you said decklists. Also, I mentioned there would be changes in how I would continue this challenge, in the form of 2 new rules: - Almost all Structure Decks have a portrait monster that indicates the Structure Deck's boss monster(s). So, for every decklist for this challenge from now on most feature said monster at 3 copies. In case that more than 1 monster is featured, to add a bit of difficulty, you can only use a combination of 3 cards among those monsters but all must be featured. Lastly, the entire playstyle of the decklist must play around either that monster(s) playstyle or turbo-ing out ASAP. - To give more ambience to the Decklists for the time they were printed, depending if they have Extra Deck monsters and the time they dayviewed, the status of the Extra Deck will change. For example: Zombie Madness will not feature an Extra Deck, Zombie World will have one, but made mostly of not-so-recent Synchros and Fusions; and Zombie Horde giving that it is the most recent one has an Extra Deck with any kind of card. So, with these explanation cleared, I bring to you the Triple Structure Deck Challenge for the Zombie Madness Structure Deck. ANALYSIS As its name states, Zombie Madness is a Structure Deck based around a Zombie-themed Deck. Giving how old this Deck was printed, it did help to show how even today Zombies' playstyle, being having a lot of GY plays. This decks' boss monster is Vampire Genesis. Is a Level 8 DARK Zombie monster with 3000 ATK/2100 DEF and it cannot be Normal Summoned/Set, must be Special Summoned from the hand by banishing 1 Vampire Lord you control and cannot be summoned by other ways. OPT: You can discard 1 Zombie monster to target another one in your GY with a lower Level than the discarded monster and Special Summon it. Vampire Lord is a Level 5 DARK Zombie with 2000 ATK/1500 DEF. If it inflicts battle damage to the opponent: You can declare either Monster/Spell/Trap cards; then your opponent must send to the GY one card of the type declared, at their choice. Also, if this card was destroyed by and opponent's card effect: It Special Summon itself back during your next Standby Phase. There's a high chance you might not recognize either of them if you played/played against current-time Vampire decks giving that both monsters can't help out with their new playstyle even if they have good Levels for their Xyz. However, said Vampire support can help out to search them out and some of the support from this same Structure Deck can cheat out Lord a bit faster. As for their playstyle, it revolves around Special Summoning Zombie monsters and milling. Yes, milling is also consider to be Zombie's secondary playstyle. BREAKDOWN ***Vampire Genesis: Main Boss Monster of the Deck. Largest body and can bring Zombies from the GY. *Dark Dust Spirit: When Normal Summoned or flipped, it destroys all other face-up monsters on the field. One off as an emergency nuke giving its Spirit monster nature. ***Vampire Lord: Necessary to summon Genesis, easy to summon and tolerable stats/self-revival. ***Pyramid Turtle: When destroyed by battle, it can float into any Zombie monster from your Deck with 2000 or less DEF. Except for Genesis, it can float into any Zombie from this Deck, more importantly Lord and Spirit Reaper. ***Soul-Absorbing Bone Tower: Cannot be targeted for attacks if you control another Zombie monster, including another copy of itself so you can prevent your opponent from attacking them at all. Also, each time you Special Summon a Zombie monster on your field, it mills the top 2 cards from your opponent's Deck. ***Spirit Reaper: Cannot be destroyed by battle, but it self-destructs if it is targeted by a card effect. Mainly used for stalling out battles. **Vampire Follower(Outside Support): Searchs "Vampire" backrow when Special Summoned and it can revive itself from the GY. **Vampire Familiar(Outside Support): Searchs "Vampire" monsters when Special Summoned and it can revive itself from the GY. Main searcher for Genesis and Lord. ***Allure of Darkness(Outside Support): Giving that this deck runs a lot of DARK monsters, it adds that necessary draw power. ***Book of Life: It targets a Zombie on your GY and one monster on your opponent's GY, then it Special Summons the first target while banishing the second. A brick on turn 1 but useful later. ***Mystical Space Typhoon: Quick-play backrow removal. ***Call of the Mummy: Basically Valhalla for Zombie monsters. *Vampire Kingdom(Outside Support): Boosts Zombie monsters and turns Lord's and Bone Tower's mill effect into a potential destruction effect as well. *Vampire Takeover(Outside Support): Activates Kingdom from the Deck and revives a "Vampire". One of Follower's main searchs. *Vampire Awakening(Outside Support): Special Summons a "Vampire" monster from the Deck but destroys it during the End Phase. Useful to summon Familiar/Follower to search. ***Torrential Tribute: Another emergency board wipe. **Compulsory Evacuation Device: Targeted bouncing effect.

deck_name: Eldlich Albaz deck Dec. 2021 (Kintoki the Golden Dragon)
deck_excerpt: (Eldlich Albaz deck December 2021. And also a Fate/Grand Order reference.)
deck_description: My third Albaz deck in a row this week. For today, I got an Eldlich Albaz deck profile, named after one of Japan's most famous fairy tales and Fate/Grand Order's strongest Servants, Sakata Kintoki. AKA, the Golden Boy!  ...I'm not even joking. Kintoki's original name "Kintaro" literally means "Golden boy" in Japanese. And his father was a dragon, while his mother was a man-eating witch. So the name is kind of appropriate.     Although this deck runs a total of 12 hand traps--14 if you count Eldlich the Golden Lord, you would rather be going first most of the time so you can set up as many negates and disruptions as possible. Eldlich is one of the best monsters to send to the Graveyard with Branded Fusion, since it can then revive itself if you send a set Spell/Trap on your field to the Graveyard.

deck_name: Floowandereeze Deck 2021 (DEC)- A Journey Across the Atlantic
deck_description:
The faraway birds   Ah birds… the other warm-blooded animal that I always forget. Almost like modern day dinosaurs, thoses (almost all the time) little creatures are in every continent of our world while being one of the most common animals that you’ll see. One of the most famous birds is the not so impressive Arctic tern (Sterna paradisaea) , a bird that flies enormous distances compared to another being, almost 70. 000 kilometers (in normal units) or 46. 000 miles (in burguer units), travelling literare around the world. And that journey, my fellow traveler, is where Floowandereeze starts.   Let’s begin our journey   Above everything, the Floowandereeze archetype is about a journey of 3 littler Arctic terns (the Floowandereezes) flying in their migratory route, from Greenland or Iceland to the Antarctic continent. It has a control style of play, with so many cards that are stalls on leg, like  Floowandereeze & Empen  who prevents any special summon  monsters from active its effect while in atk mode or, Floowandereeze & Snowl who is a evolution of Ultimate Conductor Tyranno, that can flip face down any special summon monster  in your opponent field. But how does this deck work? Unlike any other meta contender this deck doesn't perform any special summon. At first this sounds weird, doesn't it? But don’t fear, my fellow traveller,because our destiny point will guide us along the way. Every low level Floowandereeze monster has the effect that when you normal summon it an effect is activated and soon after you can perform another normal summon, with the down side that prevents you to special summon in this turn. Furthermore, when they leave the field they go to the banned pile instead of  GY, while letting your GY completely empty. Thus , you lose your monster , right? WRONG!!  When you normal summon a winged beast monster the can be added to hand once more, even if it were tributed in this right moment. “The best way to describe Flundereeze is if a True Draco player and a monarch player made custom cards together”  once said GioGio. We have cards like Floowandereeze & Eglen (representing the USA) and Floowandereeze & Robina (representing England) , that are starters of this deck . The first one searches any Winged-best with +7 star then you can normal summon winged beast monster from your hand, and the latter one can search any -4 star from you deck then normal summon any  winged beast monster from you hand. That is superb because Robina can used as an extender to add Barrier Statue of the Stormwinds or D. D. Crow  to your hand, and summon it after you out a big board monster or you can search any low level Floowandereeze  to help in yours plays; Eglen in other hand bring to you hand cards like the already mentioning Floowandereeze & Snowl and Floowandereeze & Empen,  and further cards like Mist Valley Apex Avian and Simorgh, Lord of the Storm,  the Apex being a excellent negate and Simorgh, Lord of the Storm  a really annoying card, but almost every time you’ll search Empen, because it has an ability of search any spell / trap Floowandereeze  card. Other low level Floowandereeze monsters are Floowandereeze & Toccan (representing my home country, Brazil) and Floowandereeze & Stri (representing the Sahel region from Africa, possibly Sengal or  Mauritania). Toccan can add any Floowandereeze card that is banished to your hand then soon after normal summon any winged monster from your hand;  The angry Stri is your portable D. D. Crow,  that can banish any card from either Gy to perform its Floowandereeze effect being a powerful interrupt in the opponent turn.    The friends along the way   As I said before, the GY is empty , so you can use the most devilish tech in this format, Dimensional shifter, a portable  macro cosmo that can literally extort your opponent to pass his/her turn. And the most deadly of all, you can use it further down the duel because you GY will be almost every time empty.  Did This angry dude mess with this deck? Absolutely no, he is almost an  honorable  Floowandereeze monster. Pots will be our “baggage” in specific: Pot of Extravagance and Pot of Duality . The first one would be better if were a Prosperity, but you can never complain about what you have, and the second one is perfect since you don’t have to special summon. They can fulfill your hand in no time and accelerate your plays. Another special  baggage is Gold Sarcophagus, an awesome card to search any low level Floowandereeze. Our map to fortune is Floowandereeze and the Magnificent Map, which (alongside Floowandereeze and the Dreaming Town) is one of the most powerful items in your journey. It grants you the ability to have an extra normal summon by revealing a Floowandereeze monster and banishing a different  Floowandereeze card  from your deck and then normal summoning that first monster... phew... and if you a another low level Floowandereeze,  you can add to your hand by its effect and is not over yet: if your opponent normal summon a monster , you can normal summon a Floowandereeze monster from your hand, in another word, in case that your opponent interrupt your plays you can know play in his/her turn like nothing really happened. Floowandereeze and the Dreaming Town  does the same thing, with an additional effect that you can banish this card and flip face down every monster that were special summon  in your opponent turn. Both of these cards are what make this deck so fearsome to play against. For our final Floowandereeze  card we have Floowandereeze and the Unexplored Winds: an archetype Soul exchange card. Not so useful , but come on… that’s a really good looking card, like a good summer’s sunset after a really long year in school.   Spice tech!!!
  • Dimensional Barrier: damn you sword so players!!
  • Ghost Reaper & Winter Cherries: since its extra deck doesn’t matter I decide to throw this deck on the side, making your opponent sweat in the process;
  • Harpie's Feather Storm and Harpie's Feather Duster:  These cards work amazingly with this deck , since almost all monsters are WIND winged beasts, and Harpie's Feather Storm is basically a skip a turn, definitely 3 of,  and finally can search Harpie's Feather Duster if destroyed.
  Combos   Basic combo: using just one Robina
  1. Normal summon Robina an then search Eglen;
  2. Immediately normal summon Eglen that you searched and then search Empen;
  3. Immediately tribute summon Empen;
  4. Chain link 1 Empen, chain link 2 Robina, chain link 3 Eglen;
  5. Eglen and Robina go to your hand, Empen searches dreaming town;
Map+Robina: 1xMagnificent map+1Robina
  1. Activate Map, use its effect revealing Robina, banish Eglen from your deck and immediately summoning Robina;
  2. Chain link 1 Robina chain link 2 Eglen;
  3. Eglen goes to your hand, robina searches Barrier statue of the Stormwinds then immediately summons Eglen;
  4. Eglen searches Empen, immediately tribute summon Empen;
  5. Cl1 Empen, cl2 Robina, cl3 Eglen;
  6. Eglen and Robina go to the hand, Empen searches dreaming town then immediately summons Barrier statue of the Stormwinds;
Thanks GioGio for help figure out this combos (Link for his/her deck) Conclusion After this amazing journey we stand upon this magnificent view, ICE, ICE everywhere,even because we arrived in Antarctica, land of the penguin ahaha. Jokes aside, this deck is one of the most enjoyable to play  in recent years, and if you saw my  Paleozoic Frog deck ,  you know that I love natural history, and seeing the amazing arts of these incredible birds was a pleasure… Man...  What amazing birds. I hope you enjoyed this guide as much as I enjoyed writing it. Stay tuned for more Floowanderezees guides (now with a Dogmatika package).
Kuriboh

Toons are fun! So are huge monsters! So turn Toon Kingdom's cost into a benefit for Gren Maju da Eiza and Eater of Millions.  Doesn't scale fast enough? Throw in pot of desires to both make it easier to draw into something to find a Toon Kingdom and to supercharge your Gren Maju.  Interested in defense? Just stick a Lvl 4 Toon Monster with Toon Kingdom and wait for the payoff. Do additional deck filtering with the strange Goblin Circus, or shut down opponent removal forever with Cursed Seal of the Forbidden Spell - especially since you don't always need your second Toon Table of Contents.     A little hard to call this casual with the cost of Toon Black Luster Soldier and Toon Bookmark. Toon Black Luster Solider isn't required, though. Just swap him out for some more Lvl 4 Toons. One of his bigger benefits is that he doesn't need Toons on the field in order to jump in. Also feel free to add in Toon Page Flip if you want to juice it up even more.
